SIMPLE: induration
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Induration
<hw>In`du*ra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>induration</ets>, L. <ets>induratio</ets> hardness of
heart.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of hardening, or the process of growing
hard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>State of being indurated, or of having become
hard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hardness of character, manner, sensibility, etc.;
obduracy; stiffness; lack of pliancy or feeling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A certain <qex>induration</qex> of character had arisen from long
habits of business.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indusial</ent>⟦br⟧
